[[Return to the ground floor.|School ground floor]]
<<else>>
[[Explore the upper floor.|School upper]]
<<endif>>

::School ground floor

You find yourself back outside the door to Mr. Schue's office, waiting.

"I know it's going to be difficult," Mr. Schue says, his voice muffled through the wood. "but I think we can work together on this. You've already put things in motion."

"I don't know what you want me to do," Kurt says. "My dad's in the hospital, and I haven't even started--"

"People have begun to take an interest. We don't know how word got out, but we do know that it's only going to get more difficult from here. We need to start immediately. "

The response takes too long. You tap your feet against the old tile, waiting. "I'll think about it," Kurt says. "I can't make a decision like this while-- while my dad is still recovering."

"Of course," Mr. Schue says. He opens the door. "I hope that we've established enough here to keep working together going forward. I'm sure your father would agree."

Kurt's face is still and serious. He looks less like the confused young man you met in a hospital room and more like someone who could tear apart his opponents in the council chambers without even breaking into a sweat. "Maybe," he says. "Thanks for meeting with me, but I really need to go back to my father."

He heads for the exit, his footsteps steady and sure. It's still a nice day when you get outside. The sun is bright, and the air is cool.  The school faces the street of a leafy residential neighborhood, mostly empty while everyone is at work or in school. The wind rustles the nearby trees.

Kurt looks at you. "What next?" he asks.

"We can bring you back across the border immediately," you say. It doesn't have to be right now, but it sounds like Kurt's anxious to get back to the hospital. "Or--" 

"Okay," he says. "That first thing. Let's do that."

"Sure," you say. Wes had you borrow the company car, and it's sitting in the parking lot, waiting for you.

[[Leave the school behind.|Leave school]]

::Leave school

Kurt is quiet during most of the car ride, but when you get out to walk the rest of the way, he seems to work up some sort of courage to say something else. There's a certain places near the border where taking a car is risky, even in Under. The sound of the engine can make the guards patrolling the border more alert, and it's easier to travel by foot undetected. You leave the car hidden in a tucked away alley and walk the rest of the way through the narrow city streets.

"Your name's Blaine, right?" Kurt asks. He touches your wrist, where you're still wearing the watch your father gave you when you turned twelve. You still get it a new battery every few years, and you've replaced the leather band once, after it became too worn. Kurt's skin is soft, pampered where it's touching your own. But that's not fair of you. It wasn't so long ago when your hands were like that too.

"Yes," you say.

He draws his hand back. "Before, when you said they were coming for me," Kurt says, "I thought you meant the government, and that it was about-- about me, specifically and not about the work."

"That's just what Mr. Schue told me to say." You tilt your head to one side. "What do you mean, about you?"

He takes a deep breath, steeling himself. "That I'm gay."

"Oh," you say. "You know they won't care, right? Not as long as you're willing to--" You figured all this stuff out [[when you were fourteen|fourteen]], and you know every rationalization, every last ditch attempt to feel normal.

"Yeah," Kurt says, "but I don't want-- I didn't want to have to lie like that, not about who I am. My dad-- he understands that about me."

You watch him as he seems to fold into himself, uncertain and unsure, the insecurity takes years of his face. "That's why I left," you say. "I didn't want to keep hiding."

He blinks. Once. Twice. "You're--"

"Yes," you say. "I am." You like the way it sounds when you say it, a simple fact. It took you so long to say it out loud, to put it out there without fear, and now it feels almost easy.

His eyes go round and wide and the tiniest hint of a smile curl at the edge of his lips, surprised and pleased. You can almost imagine what he must look like when he's happy. "I don't think-- I've never met anyone like me before. No one who was willing to admit it anyway."

"It's not so unusual," you say, "over here."

"I'd heard that," he says, "but I hadn't--"

You shrug.

[[Reach the border.|Reach border]]

::Reach border

The border looms ahead, concrete walls, barbed wire, guards at various checkpoints, though they're few and far between. "Come on," you say. "We're almost there." On the Over side of things, nothing exists within 100 feet of the wall that protects the border, but on Under, the city buildings grow right up against it. You see people walking by there all the time. You even got invited to a block party right next to it, once.

You find the particular place you like to use, where there's a gap in the wall, hidden with a sheet of painted fabric, thick and heavy and carefully maintained on both sides. You lift the fabric, gesturing for Kurt to go through first. He hesitates for just a moment before he ducks underneath the fabric, squeezing himself through the gap in the wall. Maybe he doesn't quite trust you yet. It wouldn't be the first time someone has questioned your motives..

When you're back in Over, Kurt takes a deep breath, like he's trying reacclimate to the air on this side of the border, like it's different somehow.

"Are you okay from here?" you ask. The people who came after him in the hospital are probably still after him, but the hospital was an easy guess. They probably won't try again so soon, especially not on the street, where the police have cameras on every street corner, watching every move.

"Yes," he says. He smiles, for real this time. It's tinged with a warmth that surprises you, an affection that feels genuine. "Thank you for this."

You smile back. "Just doing my job. Good luck. I hope your father gets better."

"Thanks again," he says.

He turns away from you and starts walking towards the denser parts of the city. From there he can grab a bus to the hospital, see his father, maybe give him a hug. You think of all the things you left behind when you crossed the border. You're one of the few people who knows how to cross the border, but you've never gone back to see your parents, to ask them if they understood--

Would you trade places with Kurt to get it all back again?

No.

You wouldn't. You wouldn't give your choices up for anything.

