::Tina's room
<<set $tinasroom=true>>You knock once on the door before pushing your way inside. Tina is sitting on her bed, knees up next to her chest, and Mike is on the spare patch of floor doing some sort of twisting thing with his legs that looks like it shouldn't be physically possible.

"Blaine!" she shouts, jumping off the bed and pulling you into a hug. "You've been so busy lately, we haven't seen you in like a week, jerk."

Mike punches your shoulder, friendly as always. "Good to see you, man," he says.

Kurt lurks by the doorway as if he doesn't quite know what do with himself. "Come on," you say, reaching out to tug him closer by the sleeve of his shirt.

"Who is this?" Tina asks. She smacks your arm, the way she does when she thinks you've been holding out on her.

"I'm Kurt," Kurt says. "I'm-- I'm new here." He shakes both their hands. Mike gives him a slap on the back.

Tina smiles. "New, huh? I'm Tina, and this is Mike. I hope Blaine's been a good host. He can sometimes forget his manners."

"Hey," you say.

Tina rolls her eyes at you before she turns back to Kurt. "Are you coming to the Battle of the Bands tomorrow night?"

Kurt straightens his back and glances over at you. "Um," he says. "Sure, yes, I'd love that."

"Wait, that's tomorrow?" you say.

Tina rolls her eyes. "Yes, silly. It's tomorrow." You promised Mercedes and Rachel last week that you'd show up to cheer their band, Divalicious, on, and you do keep your promises. The last time you had to back out of watching the perform, Rachel left you a ten page letter in your mailbox explaining exactly why you need to work on scheduling your commitments better and how it is of the utmost importance to support friends with their struggling music careers.

"Uh, what //is// a Battle of the Bands?" Kurt asks. "They're not going to get into fistfights onstage, are they?"

"It's like a long concert with a lot of bands, but with voting at the end," Mike explains.

"Oh," Kurt says. He smiles, brighter, more comfortable with himself. "I'm looking forward to it, then."

"Good," she says. "Lucky for you, Rachel has the extra ticket she got for Brody before they broke up. It's all yours as long as you promise to keep Blaine from moping in the corner by himself."

"I don't //mope//--" you say, crossing your arms across your chest.

"I'd be happy to," Kurt says. He nudges your shoulder with his own. "No moping."

"You totally mope," Tina says. "Remember that time I caught you crying over //Gone with the Wind//? Sam had to put you through a Charlie Chaplin marathon right afterwards to cheer you up."

"That really doesn't count," you say.

"Mhm," Tina says, not sounding convinced at all. "Well, it was very nice to meet you Kurt, but Mike and I should go back to rehearsing."

"Uh, sure," Mike says, eyebrows going up, but he still stretches his arms out and bounces on his toes like he's warming up.

You mouth a 'thank you' to Tina as you tug Kurt out the door.

[[Leave.|Your apartment]]

::Your room

Your room is silent and waiting. It's clean, spare. You've never quite managed to embrace the chaos of a messy room, not even after you were allowed to. All that's left is what you can't get rid of, the things that linger on long after they should. This used to be one of the two children's bedrooms in the house. Sam got the other one, and Tina got the master bedroom. There's a closet in the corner, an old wooden dresser in one corner with a mirror sitting on top, a desk for reading and writing when you have the time.

"So those were my roommates," you say.

Kurt's expression is soft. "I liked them," he says, a warmth threading through his voice.

"And this is my room." You feel silly, wanting Kurt to, well, wanting Kurt to like it, but there's something about Kurt that makes you feel well, kind of pathetic. You can tell that he could do anything he set his mind to through sheer force of will, and you, you pretty much do whatever happens to come your way.

Kurt peers around. He leans forward and hesitates at a picture you have of you and Cooper sitting on your nightstand, aged [[five and fifteen]] respectively. Cooper has a hand resting on the top of your head, and you're wearing mis-matched smiles, yours stiff, closed-lipped, Cooper's wide and grinning. You remember taking it off your parents' dresser before you left, shoving it into your luggage and zipping it closed.

"That's my older brother and me," you say.

Kurt runs his fingers along the the frame, glancing at you like he's trying to put all the pieces back in place. "Do you miss him? I-- If I left, my brother, well, step-brother, is--"

"I see him once a week," you say. "His play is about to start next month, and he won't shut up about it. I'm supposed to go to his dress rehearsal in a few days." 

"Oh," Kurt says. His smile gets the slightest bit wider, a little affection.

"He's kind of an asshole, but he's still--" You don't really know how to fill in the rest of that sentence, how to really capture Cooper's //Cooperness//.

"-- still family." Kurt finishes for you.

"Yeah," you say, and a warm familiar feeling spreads through your chest.
